ectivity is only ~45% with Ni catalyst (rest is hydroxyacid)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_004\": 0.92},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.90,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.62,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n            \"feedback\": \"Both reactions are directly supported by experimental literature (Ritson 2021, Kitadai 2019). The Surface\u2192Hydrothermal environmental flow is unconventional\u2014surface photoproducts would need to be transported to hydrothermal settings\u2014but is not implausible (e.g., rain-out into vent systems, or intermittent exposure). Short and efficient pathway.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Justify the Surface\u2192Hydrothermal transport mechanism more explicitly\", \"Note \u03b1-HG source must itself be provisioned (e.g., from rxn_005 side product)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.92},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.90,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.62,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Excellent pathway design with the \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate recycling loop (rxn_005 produces \u03b1-HG side product \u2192 rxn_003 re-oxidizes to aKG). This is the most creative and metabolically resonant pathway in the network. Both reactions experimentally anchored. Same environmental flow concern as P3.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Emphasize the recycling loop as a proto-metabolic feature\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_006\": 0.82},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Both steps occur at the surface with UV access, making this environmentally self-consistent. ZnS photochemical reductive amination (Wang 2012) gives lower yields (0.6-7.4%) than metal-catalyzed routes but is well-documented. Surface\u2192Surface flow is coherent. Shorter pathway, fewer steps to fail.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Note the low yield of ZnS route and consider whether concentration mechanisms are needed\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.75, \"rxn_002\": 0.70, \"rxn_007\": 0.85, \"rxn_008\": 0.92, \"rxn_009\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"The most environmentally progressive pathway: Hydrothermal\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical. The phosphoro-Strecker step (Ashe 2019, 88% yield) is outstanding. Thermal decarboxylation of aKG to succinic semialdehyde is chemically sound. The 5-step length is longer but each step is well-motivated. DAP as a starting material is a reasonable assumption given its demonstrated prebiotic relevance.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Address DAP availability constraints\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 