\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Clean Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical progression with well-supported reactions. Combines Ritson upstream oxidation with Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs amination. Only 3 steps, each experimentally grounded.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same \u03b1-HG source question as other rxn_003-based pathways\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_012\": 0.88, \"rxn_013\": 0.68, \"rxn_014\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n            \"feedback\": \"The cyanohydrin capture step (rxn_012) is well-supported by Ritson 2021 (~45% capture). However, rxn_013 (ammonolysis of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile) is the weakest step mechanistically: direct displacement of hydroxyl by ammonia on a cyanohydrin is not a standard textbook transformation. The classical Strecker mechanism involves imine formation then cyanide addition, not cyanohydrin ammonolysis. This step would likely proceed via reversible loss of HCN, imine formation, then re-addition, which is valid but the stated mechanism is slightly misleading.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify the mechanism of rxn_013: likely proceeds via equilibrium HCN loss/re-addition through imine intermediate rather than direct ammonolysis\", \"Consider whether this is better represented as a two-step process\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an exceptionally well-designed synthesis network that demonstrates deep engagement with the prebiotic chemistry literature. The network excels in several dimensions: (1) **Literature alignment** is outstanding\u2014every major experimentally demonstrated route to glutamate (Kitadai FeS/Fe\u2070, Kaur Ni/meteorite, Wang ZnS photochemistry, Ashe phosphoro-Strecker, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs, Ritson HS\u207b/UV upstream) is incorporated with appropriate citations and quantitative yield awareness. The explicit exclusion of formate-based reduction (Maughan & Miller 1999 critique) shows sophisticated understanding. (2) **Topology** is excellent: \u03b1-ketoglutarate as the central hub with degree 8 is the right architectural choice, mirroring its role in both extant biochemistry and prebiotic chemistry. The \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate recycling loop (rxn_005\u2192rxn_003) is creative and metabolically prescient. (3) **Chemical diversity**: three distinct nitrogen-installation strategies (reductive amination, Strecker/phosphoro-Strecker, Bucherer-Bergs) provide genuine redundancy. (4) **Minor weaknesses**: The upstream CO\u2082\u2192pyruvate\u2192aKG hydrothermal fixation (rxn_001, rxn_002) is the least experimentally constrained segment and could benefit from more specific mineral catalyst assignments. The succinic semialdehyde 'hub' (mol_009) only has degree 2 and barely qualifies. The cyanohydrin ammonolysis step (rxn_013) has a mechanistic ambiguity. Some Surface\u2192Hydrothermal environmental transitions (P3, P4) are unconventional and could use better justification. Overall, this is a high-quality, literature-grounded network that would serve as an excellent basis for experimental validation.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.87,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.92\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.75, "rxn_002": 0.7, "rxn_004": 0.92}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.85, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overal